eans of growing cultural markets. Contemporary writers have tended to explore how their own critical capacities have become compatible with or even essential to a neoliberal economy that has embraced art's autonomous gestures as proof that authentic self-articulation and social engagement can and should occur within capitalism. Taking a sociological approach to literary criticism, Sarah Brouillette interprets major works of contemporary fiction by Monica Ali, Aravind Adiga, Daljit Nagra, and Ian McEwan alongside government policy, social science, and theoretical explorations of creative work and immaterial labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAuthorshipxEconomic aspects. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.)xEconomic aspects. 0aCultural industries. 0aCultural policy. 0aEnglish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aaesthetic autonomy. 4acontemporary literature. 4acreative economy. 4acreative industries. 4acultural policy. 4agentrification. 4aneoliberalism. 4apostindustrialism. 4asociology of literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804792431zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792431.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles